    <h2>Okay, so.</h2>
    This here is a game about trapezoids that go boom.  A complicated concept,
    I know, but we're sure you'll grasp it with time.  It has been inspired by
    some things.  A rich history of explosions, parabolas, primitive shapes and
    the deep, deep stories of the conflicts between them.  Here are some in a
    list:

    <ul>
        <li>
            It all started in BASIC in 1979.  With a game called Artillery.  No
            advanced graphics here, just code and numbers and command lines.
            You even had to type in the code for the thing from a magazine.
            The <a href="http://github.com/aanand/boomtrapezoid">code</a> for
            Boom Trapezoid would take quite a while to type out from a
            magazine, it's about 10,000 words so far.
        </li>

        <li>
            A bit later, after some revisions of the BASIC game, someone made a
            game with some graphics, imaginatively named it Artillery, and put
            it on an Apple II in 1981.
        </li>

        <li>
            Scorched Earth first happened in 1991, providing players with a
            choice of weapons and other tools for the first time.
        </li>

        <li>
            Worms happened in 1995.  It added some cute and sold lots.
        </li>

        <li>
            Death Tank happened in 1996.  It added real time.  7 people would
            sit, squeezed round a TV, pressing buttons and shouting at each
            other.
        </li>
    </ul>
</div>

